<div id="review_139004398" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/139004398" />
    <a title="Susan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1381972-susan"><img alt="Susan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1224571041p2/1381972.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/139004398?book_show_action=true">Jan 06, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Susan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Susan" href="/user/show/1381972-susan">Susan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer139004398" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4351560203162898647">O! Maeve Binchy...Ireland&apos;s own Jodi Picoult!<br/>If you prefer to not think too hard while reading; if you are amused by all things Irish; or if you&apos;ve never experienced the Binchy formula, then you would probably enjoy any number of her books. Binchy, like Picoult, is best enjoyed in isolation of any of her other writings. <br/><br/>I believe this is one of her better books, but I am probably influenced by the fact that it was the first of hers that I read. It chronicles a couple of decades of friendship bet</span>
  <span id="freeText4351560203162898647" style="display:none">O! Maeve Binchy...Ireland's own Jodi Picoult!<br />If you prefer to not think too hard while reading; if you are amused by all things Irish; or if you've never experienced the Binchy formula, then you would probably enjoy any number of her books. Binchy, like Picoult, is best enjoyed in isolation of any of her other writings. <br /><br />I believe this is one of her better books, but I am probably influenced by the fact that it was the first of hers that I read. It chronicles a couple of decades of friendship between an Irish woman and an English woman through the trials and tribulations of their lives. Nothing revolutionary there, and yet it is quite charming for the better part of the book. Or so I thought when I first read it eleven years ago anyway. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="4351560203162898647" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


